=============================
SPRING + SPRING BOOT REVISION NOTES
=============================
1. What is Spring?

Spring is a lightweight Java framework used to build enterprise applications.

Core features:

Dependency Injection (DI)

Inversion of Control (IoC)

Modular architecture (MVC, Data, Security, etc.)

Reduces boilerplate code

Promotes loose coupling

Spring manages object creation and lifecycle using a container called ApplicationContext.

2. What is Spring Boot?

Spring Boot is built on top of Spring.

It simplifies application development by:

Auto-configuration

Embedded server (Tomcat)

Starter dependencies

Minimal configuration

Production-ready features (Actuator)

Difference:

Spring:

Manual configuration

External server required

More setup

Spring Boot:

Auto-configures components

Embedded server

Faster development

Interview line:
Spring Boot reduces configuration overhead and makes Spring applications easier to build and deploy.

3. Inversion of Control (IoC)

IoC means that object creation and lifecycle management are handled by the Spring container instead of the developer.

Traditional:
Class creates its own dependencies.

Spring:
Container creates and injects dependencies.

IoC is implemented using Dependency Injection.

4. Dependency Injection (DI)

Dependency Injection is a design pattern where dependencies are provided externally rather than created inside the class.

Types of DI:

Constructor Injection (Recommended)

Setter Injection

Field Injection (Not recommended in interviews)

Why constructor injection is preferred:

Makes dependencies explicit

Supports immutability

Easier for testing

Prevents NullPointerException

Interview line:
DI promotes loose coupling and better testability.

5. Loose Coupling vs Tight Coupling

Tight Coupling:
Class directly depends on concrete implementation.

Loose Coupling:
Class depends on interface or abstraction.

Spring promotes loose coupling using DI.

Benefits:

Easier testing

Flexible implementation

Better maintainability

6. ApplicationContext

ApplicationContext is the core Spring container.

Responsibilities:

Creates beans

Manages lifecycle

Injects dependencies

Handles configuration

In Spring Boot, it is created automatically when the application starts.

7. What Happens When Spring Boot Starts?

main() method runs

SpringApplication.run() is called

ApplicationContext is created

Component scanning runs

Beans are created and initialized

Auto-configuration is applied

Embedded server starts

Application becomes ready

Important term:
DispatcherServlet handles incoming HTTP requests.

=============================
SPRING ANNOTATIONS (Detailed Explanation)
=============================
1. @SpringBootApplication

This is the main annotation in a Spring Boot application.

It is a combination of:

@Configuration

@EnableAutoConfiguration

@ComponentScan

Purpose:

Marks main class as configuration

Enables auto-configuration

Enables component scanning

Placed on the main class.

2. @Component

Generic stereotype annotation.

Marks a class as a Spring-managed bean.

Spring detects it during component scanning and registers it in ApplicationContext.

Used for:
Any generic component that does not fit in Service/Repository/Controller.

3. @Service

Specialized version of @Component.

Used for:
Business logic layer.

Purpose:

Semantically indicates business service

Makes code more readable

May have additional Spring features later

Example:
ExpenseService handles business rules.

Interview line:
@Service indicates that the class contains business logic.

4. @Repository

Specialized version of @Component.

Used for:
Data access layer.

Special feature:

Translates database exceptions into Spring’s DataAccessException.

Purpose:
Indicates interaction with database.

5. @Controller

Used in Spring MVC applications.

Returns:
View (HTML page).

Used when building:
Web apps with Thymeleaf/JSP.

6. @RestController

Combination of:

@Controller

@ResponseBody

Used for:
REST APIs.

Returns:
JSON response directly.

Most common in backend applications.

7. @Autowired

Used for Dependency Injection.

Tells Spring to inject a matching bean.

Works on:

Constructor

Field

Setter

Modern Spring:
If there is only one constructor, @Autowired is optional.

8. @ComponentScan

Tells Spring where to look for beans.

By default:
Spring scans the package of the main class and its sub-packages.

If classes are outside base package:
They will NOT be detected unless explicitly configured.

9. @Configuration

Marks a class as a source of bean definitions.

Used when defining custom beans manually using @Bean.

10. @Bean

Used inside a @Configuration class.

Purpose:
Manually register a bean in Spring container.

Used when:

Third-party classes

Custom configuration needed

QUICK INTERVIEW SUMMARY

Spring = DI + IoC framework
Spring Boot = Opinionated layer that simplifies Spring

IoC = Container controls object lifecycle
DI = Dependencies injected externally

ApplicationContext = Core Spring container

Startup Flow:
main → run → context → scan → create beans → start server

@Controller = Web MVC
@RestController = REST API
@Service = Business logic
@Repository = Data access
@Component = Generic bean
